our-eyes/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 06 Dec 2012 15:39:30 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"News";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Thoughts on Time";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:23:"http://time.ly/?p=22749";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:337:"Most of our experiences of events have the same structure. We experience events in time in aÂ linear fashion. These experiences of events, though sometimes a little dull, are perfectly normal. Itâ€™s that familiar drudgeÂ of one thing after another! But there &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/life-flashes-before-your-eyes/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Jonathan";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5803:"<div id="attachment_22754" class="wp-caption alignleft" style="width: 310px"><a href="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Roger_Blackwell.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-22754" title="Roger_Blackwell" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Roger_Blackwell-300x221.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="221" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Photo by Roger Blackwell, courtesy of Creative Commons</p></div>\n<p>Most of our experiences of events have the same structure. We experience events in time in aÂ linear fashion. These experiences of events, though sometimes a little dull, are perfectly normal.</p>\n<p>Itâ€™s that familiar drudgeÂ of one thing after another! But there are some rare experiences that areÂ very different. These are experiences where all (or at least many) of the events of our lives â€˜flashÂ before our eyesâ€™ seemingly all at once. These cases, unlike those that we normally experience,Â seem to be ones where the regular succession of events is interrupted and we experiences wholeÂ sections of our past lives in a single instant (or similarly short interval of time).</p>\n<p>In many ways these experiences seem really strange. Not only are these cases where peopleÂ report re-living events from the past, they are sometimes also associated with a sense of timeÂ slowing down and everything becoming clear. Of course, it seems peculiar to say that time reallyÂ slows down in these cases, or that we really can experience all of those events from our lives.Â After all, if those events took so many years to occur, how can I possibly experience them in theÂ very brief time it takes for Â my life to flash before my eyes?</p>\n<p>Strange as they may be, these experiences are reasonably well documented (as a quick internetÂ search reveals!) in a range of different cultures. Whatâ€™s striking form our own culture is thatÂ these kinds of experience (of many events flashing before our eyes) are generally supposed to beÂ closely associated with â€˜near death experiencesâ€™, other features of which include an awareness ofÂ being dead, moving through a tunnel and communicating with light.<br />\n<div id="attachment_22753" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 310px"><a href="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/MikeBaird1.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-22753" title="MikeBaird" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/MikeBaird1-300x300.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="300" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Photo by Mike Baird, courtesy of Creative Commons</p></div> But in fact, in scientific studies, it doesnâ€™t seem that there is such a close association. This experience of events where oneâ€™s life seeming to flash by all at once is sometimes referred to as â€˜life review&#8217;and, in one study at least, was only present in 13% of Near Death Experiences.1Â (One other interesting feature of near death experiences is that although patients most viewÂ themselves as being close to death one study showed that of 58 such patients only 28 were in factÂ in a condition such that, had they not had medical intervention, they would have died). 2</p>\n<p>Historically, such experiences as having oneâ€™s life flash before oneâ€™s eyes have taken on aÂ good deal of religious significance and continue to do so today for some people. Even wereÂ such experiences to not in fact be caused by any supranatural involvement, this would beÂ unsurprising. Instances of near death experiences frequently lead to people re-examining theirÂ lives and changing the way that they do things.3</p>\n<p>Increasingly, though, thereâ€™s evidence that near death experiences themselves can be explainedÂ without recourse to any supranatural being. Indeed, many of the features of near deathÂ experiences can be triggered simply by stimulating particular regions of the brain.4 Similarly,Â there are plausible explanations of the mechanisms by which near death experiences in generalÂ might be brought about by low CO2 levels in the bloodstream.5</p>\n<p>But, be that as it may, there remains a particular fascination with these kinds of experience. EvenÂ if we can ultimately give a scientific explanation for their occurrences, these experiences are soÂ unlike our normal experiences of events in time that they certainly give rise to a sense of wonder.</p>\n<p>I suspect, though, that regardless of any explanation of the cause of these experiences (be thatÂ scientific or otherwise) we would do well to take some advice from a reasonably well-knownÂ quotation that I gather is due to Gerard Way6: â€œOne day your life will flash before your eyes. MakeÂ sure it&#8217;s worth watchingâ€.</p>\n<p>1 van Lommel, P. van Wees,, R. Meyers,V and Elfferich, I. 2001. â€˜Near-death experience inÂ survivors of cardiac arrest: a prospective study in the Netherlandsâ€™, Lancet, 358, 2039-45, p. 2041<br />\n2 Owens, J.E., Cook, E.W., Stevenson, I. 1990. â€˜Features of &#8220;near-death experience&#8221; in relation toÂ whether or not patients were near deathâ€™, Lancet, 336, 1175-1177<br />\n3 Again, see the 2001 Lancet piece.<br />\n4 See Mobbs, D. and Watt, C. 2011. â€˜There is nothing paranormal about near-death experiences:Â how neuroscience can explain seeing bright lights, meeting the dead, or being convinced you areÂ one of themâ€™, Trends in Cognitive Science, 15, 447-9<br />\n5 <a href="http://ccforum.com/content/14/2/R56" class="autohyperlink" title="http://ccforum.com/content/14/2/R56" target="_blank">ccforum.com/content/14/2/R56</a><br />\n6 <a href="http://www.goodreads.com/quotes/254656-one-day-your-life-will-flash-before-your-eyes-make" class="autohyperlink" title="http://www.goodreads.com/quotes/254656-one-day-your-life-will-flash-before-your-eyes-make" target="_blank">www.goodreads.com/quotes/254656-one-day-your-life-will-flash-before-your-eyes-make</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:50:"http://time.ly/life-flashes-before-your-eyes/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:41:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		"