a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"admin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6403:"<p><a href="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Screen-Shot-2012-08-28-at-1.01.54-PM.png"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-8673" title="Screen Shot 2012-08-28 at 1.01.54 PM" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Screen-Shot-2012-08-28-at-1.01.54-PM-300x220.png" alt="" width="300" height="220" /></a>The online events calendar has become a mainstay for many businesses and organizations the world over but often these calendars are treated as exclusive listings where the only events featured are the ones directly hosted or connected to the event publisher. This might seem like an obvious default for many businesses and organizations but for those months when only a few events are planned it can mean a rather sparse looking calendar, and empty calendars have a way of implying low organizational activity, not the most desirable impression you want to leave with your website visitors.</p>\n<p>For that reason one of the Â things we champion here at Timely is the idea of the<a href="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Screen-Shot-2012-08-28-at-1.17.42-PM.png"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-8675" title="Screen Shot 2012-08-28 at 1.17.42 PM" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Screen-Shot-2012-08-28-at-1.17.42-PM-300x221.png" alt="" width="300" height="221" /></a> &#8220;Curated Calendar.&#8221; Over the last few years the internet has taken on an interesting new dynamic. As the information available online has exploded, a new social layer has been necessary to sift through the content (news, blogs, photos, videos etc) and separate the wheat from the chaff so to speak. This has given rise to a practice known asÂ <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Media_curation">content curation</a>, usually dedicated <a href="http://www.brainpickings.org/">individuals</a> and sometimes whole <a href="http://flavorpill.com/newyork">companies</a>Â motivated by a mandate to filter and serve only the best of the best information on a certain topic or interest. When you curate content and you do it well, it can become a powerful brand marketing strategy as it builds you a reputation as a trusted and desirable source for top quality information on a certain topic, and if you can save people time and effort searching through all the choice the web offers them you&#8217;ll quickly develop a loyal following.</p>\n<p>Curating event content is just as important. Let&#8217;s say you&#8217;re a fundraising organization for cancer research, and you have 10 big fundraising events each year, galas, marathons, auctions etc. Spreading those events out over a 12 month/365 day calendar may leave you with a fairly empty looking events schedule month to month but if you also seek out relatable events you could fill your calendar with a diverse range of interesting and valuable opportunities for your members. For example: talks from <a href="http://www.ted.com/talks/jay_bradner_open_source_cancer_research.html">cancer researchers</a>, local or international <a href="http://www.worldcancercongress.org/">medical conferences</a>, book launches, <a href="http://www.webmd.com/prostate-cancer/features/fifty-years-of-milestones-in-cancer-research">research milestones</a>, member get-togethers- a whole range of event experiences that may not be directly tied to the organization itself yet would still enrich the learning and development of your members. Your members will seek out your calendar not only because of your events but also because they&#8217;ll recognize it as the definitive calendar for all events related to cancer research.</p>\n<p><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-8671" title="Screen Shot 2012-08-28 at 12.21.20 PM" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Screen-Shot-2012-08-28-at-12.21.20-PM-300x168.png" alt="" width="300" height="168" /></p>\n<p>Obviously one daunting task of populating a calendar with outside events is the extra work it would require for administrators, and that&#8217;s where a little &#8220;machine curation&#8221; can come in handy. With Timely&#8217;s All-in-One Event Calendar we&#8217;ve taken a lot of the leg work out of populating your calendar by making it really easy to syndicate and subscribe to calendar feeds from other calendars, even non-Ai1EC&#8217;s. This means that when you find a complimentary events calendar you love, you can easily <a href="http://help.time.ly/customer/portal/articles/504373-how-do-i-import-a-calendar-from-outlook-google-calendar-ical-">subscribe to the .ics feed</a> and add it to your Ai1EC&#8217;s Calendar Feeds, tagging it and categorizing it as you desire.</p>\n<p>The events from the calendars you subscribe to are then fed into your calendar on a daily basis, maintaining all their information and formatting. You have thus provided a curated feed of relatable events to your calendar visitors and organization members with a simple one time set-up that will fill your calendar with fresh event content as it&#8217;s posted by the event publisher.</p>\n<h3>Here are 6 tips for creating a great curated events calendar:</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Think outside the typical &#8220;Event&#8221; definition &#8211; </strong>events could come from anywhere, they could be international or local, they could be attendance events or simply notable anniversaries orÂ occasionsÂ that relate to your industry. Don&#8217;t get trapped in the typical &#8220;local event&#8221; model.</li>\n<li><strong>Make connections with sister organizations,</strong>Â share your events with theirs and vice versa.</li>\n<li><strong>Check the calendars of notable speakers, authors or personalities &#8211; </strong>seek out the notable individuals who relate to your brand Â and subscribe to their calendar feeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Aggregate event feeds from local news media and tourism event calendars </strong>- They may not all be on the .ics format but if they are you can easily grab individual events or entire calendars into your Ai1EC.</li>\n<li><strong>Allow community event submissions</strong> &#8211; The All-in-One can be set up to allow community members to post their own events (with moderator review) a great way of gathering event content from your very own community</li>\n<li><strong>Subscribe to member calendars</strong> &#8211; If other members in your organization host events and feature them on event calendars (Ai1EC or otherwise) you can have their events feed into your calendar.</li>\n</ol>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:57:"http://time.ly/tips-for-creating-a-curated-calendar/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"4";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:44:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:36:"Feature Event: GROW Big or GROW Home";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:51:"http://time.ly/feature-event-grow-big-or-grow-home/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:60:"http://time.ly/feature-event-grow-big-or-grow-home/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Tue, 21 Aug 2012 20:34:08 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:15:"Featured Events";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"News";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:22:"http://time.ly/?p=5799";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:363:"Perhaps you&#8217;ve already heard but Timely is a &#8220;start-up&#8221; one of thoseÂ fascinating creatures of modern business that compulsively seeks to innovate, disrupt and ultimately solve some issue or demand in our society, (even ones we&#8217;re not yet aware of). Â The &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/feature-event-grow-big-or-grow-home/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"admin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5017:"<p><a href="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/clip_image001.jpeg"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-5802" title="clip_image001" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/clip_image001-282x300.jpeg" alt="" width="282" height="300" /></a>Perhaps you&#8217;ve already heard but Timely is a &#8220;<em>start-up&#8221; </em>one of thoseÂ fascinating creatures of modern business that compulsively seeks to innovate, disrupt and ultimately solve some issue or demand in our society, (even ones we&#8217;re not yet aware of). Â The issue we seek to solve is the one of <em>event search and discovery,</em>Â namely how to help people find all the events happening in their given area and help people/businesses/organizations publish and connect events more easily. Â After all, how weÂ perceiveÂ our time is very much tied to the quality of the experiences we have with it and being fully aware of all the experiences available to us gives us the opportunity for that magical outcome ofÂ <em>time well spent</em>, and if we&#8217;re lucky evenÂ <em>the</em> <em>time of our lives.Â </em></p>\n<p>Having the time of our lives is exactly what we plan on doing this week at <a href="http://growconf.com/">GROWÂ </a><a href="http://growconf.com/">Conference</a>Â (<a href="https://twitter.com/#!/search/%23growconf">#GROWconf</a>) in Vancouver, one of North America&#8217;s (nay the world&#8217;s!)Â premier events for start-up culture, industry and dialogue.</p>\n<div><a href="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/happening_1339783300.jpeg"><img class="size-full wp-image-5804 alignright" title="happening_1339783300" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/happening_1339783300.jpeg" alt="" width="250" height="200" /></a>This is the sort of place where deals are made, funding can be found, partnerships ignite and small companies make the inroads they need to become BIG companies. It&#8217;s a place of networking for sure but it&#8217;s also a place of growth, real entrepreneurial growth not just in funding opportunities but in terms of intellectual evolution for what it means to be a successful start-up in today&#8217;s world of dynamic technology and design.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>So much happens at this one event that it can be a little overwhelming; conferences (of course), seminars, guest speakers, workshops, tours, launches, after-parties, kite boarding! It&#8217;s a wonderland of entrepreneurial activity and spirit and this week it&#8217;s our <strong>feature event</strong>, not because we happen to be there or that it happens to be centered around the very nature of our business but because it exemplifies what we considerÂ <em>a life changing event.Â </em></div>\n<div></div>\n<div><a href="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Screen-Shot-2012-08-21-at-1.23.15-PM.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-5809" title="Screen Shot 2012-08-21 at 1.23.15 PM" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Screen-Shot-2012-08-21-at-1.23.15-PM-e1345580608856-300x277.png" alt="" width="240" height="222" /></a></div>\n<div></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>When you put so many <a href="http://growconf.com/sessions/?id=6#talks">great thinkers</a> and status quo shakers into a few <a href="http://growconf.com/venue/">city blocks of downtown Vancouver</a>, something magicalÂ happens, actually lots of little magical things happen to many different people in many different places. An entrepreneur or perhaps a budding one, may enter as one thing and come out another. It&#8217;s transformative and we happen to think that a truly great event should lead you toÂ indelibleÂ experiences that shape you or your ideas in some transformative way.</div>\n<div>\n<p>This year at GROW we hope to be transformed and we hope to transform. We&#8217;re looking to share <a href="http://time.ly/event-search-calendar/">our ideas</a> about how events should be published and discovered online and we&#8217;re hoping those very ideas evolve in the process of sharing them.</p>\n<p>This week at Grow you can find Timely CEO <a href="https://twitter.com/riklogtenberg">Rik Logtenberg</a> and Timely co-founder and VP Community <a href="https://twitter.com/BradleyRoulston">Bradley Roulston</a> strutting their stuff down the busy conference halls and happy-hour pow-wows. If you want to talk the future of event search and publishing please get in touch:</p>\n<div class="pull-left">Twitter: <a href="https://twitter.com/riklogtenberg">@Hubrik</a></p>\n<p><a href="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/IMG_4239_reasonably_small.jpeg"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-5805" title="IMG_4239_reasonably_small" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/IMG_4239_reasonably_small.jpeg" alt="" width="128" height="128" /></a></div>\n<div class="pull-left">Twitter:Â <a href="https://twitter.com/BradleyRoulston#">@BradleyRoulston</a></p>\n<p><a style="color: #005580; text-decoration: underline;" href="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/2397c8b.jpeg"><img title="2397c8b" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/2397c8b.jpeg" alt="" width="128" height="128" /></a></div>\n</div>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:56:"http://time.ly/feature-event-grow-big-or-grow-home/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"0";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:44:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n			\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:62:"Announcing v1.8 with Posterboard View and Facebook Integration";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:78:"http://time.ly/announcing-v1-8-with-posterboard-view-and-facebook-integration/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:87:"http://time.ly/announcing-v1-8-with-posterboard-view-and-facebook-integration/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 30 Jul 2012 18:24:58 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"News";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8:"Releases";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:20:"http://time.ly/?p=44";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:425:"Bum-badda-bah, trumpets please&#8230; We&#8217;re thrilled to announce the much anticipated,Â painstakingly constructed, feverishly finalized, feature packed upgrade to The All-in-One Event Calendar plugin &#8211; premium versionÂ 1.8! Now this is a major upgrade with a lot of new features that we&#8217;re really &#8230; <a href="http://time.ly/announcing-v1-8-with-posterboard-view-and-facebook-integration/">Continued</a>";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"admin";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4134:"<p><a href="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/v1.8.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-106" style="border: 1px solid black;" title="v1.8" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/v1.8-300x259.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="259" /></a>Bum-badda-bah, trumpets please&#8230; We&#8217;re thrilled to announce the much anticipated,Â painstakingly constructed, feverishly finalized, feature packed upgrade to The All-in-One Event Calendar plugin &#8211; premium versionÂ 1.8! Now this is a major upgrade with a lot of new features that we&#8217;re really excited about, but before we send you off on an upgrading / downloading frenzy read this <strong>IMPORTANT NOTICE:</strong></p>\n<p>Due to a slight bug in the previous version of the Ai1EC (v1.7.1) current 1.7.1 users will need to download a special patch plugin in order to have a trouble free-upgrade (If you&#8217;re installing from scratch or from an earlier version like 1.7 then you can simply download the v1.8 Premium directly from <a href="http://time.ly">Time.ly)</a>.</p>\n<p>For all you 1.7.1 users watch this <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ex2d3oqMTSU&amp;feature=youtu.be">quick tutorialÂ video</a> on how to do the upgrade</p>\n<p><img class="alignright  wp-image-110" style="border: 1px solid black;" title="Screen Shot 2012-07-26 at 4.06.58 PM" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Screen-Shot-2012-07-26-at-4.06.58-PM-e1343428763313-1024x741.png" alt="" width="400" height="289" /></p>\n<p>Now on to the fun stuff! Version 1.8 Premium includes a feature that gives you an entirely new way of displaying your calendar to your website visitors. It&#8217;s called <strong>Posterboard View</strong> and it may very well alter the <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calendar">entireÂ </a></em><em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calendar">course of event calendar evolution</a>. </em>Okay a little heavy on the hyperbole but for us Posterboard represents something truly different for the online events calendar. You see Posterboard view breaks with the grid / list layout of the traditional calendar by presenting your events more like a community bulletin board, with emphasis on the featured image of each event. It&#8217;s more visual, more attractive and ultimately more engaging for your calendar visitors. Posterboard will work especially well for users like clubs, concert halls, <a href="http://spiritbar.inthekoots.com/">music venues</a>, and theatres who regularly post photos or artwork for their events (i.e. concert posters)Â and want to show them off without having to click to get the event details. Â It&#8217;s almost like <a href="http://pinterest.com/clevercaliber/calendars-of-our-lives/">Pinterest</a> for events ; )</p>\n<p><a href="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Screen-Shot-2012-07-30-at-12.29.26-PM-e1343677109837.png"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-124" style="border: 1px solid black; margin-top: 2px; margin-bottom: 2px;" title="Screen Shot 2012-07-30 at 12.29.26 PM" src="http://time.ly/wp-timely/assets/Screen-Shot-2012-07-30-at-12.29.26-PM-e1343677109837.png" alt="" width="360" height="202" /></a>AlsoÂ new in this release is the long awaited<a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ryd5s06KezI&amp;feature=plcp" target="_blank">Â Facebook Integration</a>Â feature that allows Ai1EC owners to import and export events directly to and from Facebook. This feature allows you to subscribe to your personal events on Facebook (i.e. the ones you&#8217;ve joined orcreated) as well as the eventsofÂ friends, fan/business pages and groups.</p>\n<p><strong>Other new features include:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The ability to lock the calendar to a particular view (Posterboard, month, agenda, etc)</li>\n<li>Improved (refactored) javascript which should dramatically reduce conflicts with other plugins</li>\n<li>A variety of UI / UX improvements</li>\n<li>Our new &#8220;Timely&#8221; branding : )</li>\n</ul>\n<div>Well we hope you enjoy version 1.8 and we look forward to your feedback. As always for technical support or development inquiries contact us at <a href="help.time.ly">help.time.ly.</a></div>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:83:"http://time.ly/announcing-v1-8-with-posterboard-view-and-facebook-integration/feed/";s:7:"attribs";